reviewText: With all of Diana's wonderful films that remain unreleased here in the States (and elsewhere), somehow these two very minor entries wind up being delivered. "An Alligator Named Daisy" only co-stars Diana in a small role, the real star being the annoyingly precocious Jean Carson in a tale about a stuffy Brit who winds up with an alligator and must keep it in order to keep the girl he is interested in (Carson). Blink too often and you will miss Diana's all too few onscreen appearances. "Value For Money" features Diana in a more prominent role about a cheapskate guy who falls for cabaret singer (Dors) and tries to defy his inner miser in order to woo her with the money he has plenty of. Both of these comedy "classics" are very corny and not very enjoyable, I can only recommend them to the extremely hardcore Diana Dors fan, or if such a thing exists, Jean Carson fans. Lets get some of Diana's real classics, like "The Unholy Wife" and "Yeild To The Night" released before forgettable duds like these two clunkers.
